r to say that they date to 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it is perhaps less clear =
what they mean for corporate governance. Maybe nothing. But you could sketc=
h some theories:
=09Meme stocks are basically companies whose shares are largely held by ent=
husiastic retail investors who are on Reddit a lot.=09In some ways, this re=
sembles Phase 2 of my stylized history: You have diffuse retail shareholder=
s and powerful managers who run the companies; the tools that institutional=
 investors developed to supervise managers in Phase 3 don=E2=80=99t really =
work at companies that don=E2=80=99t have institutional investors.=C2=A0=09=
In other ways, though, it=E2=80=99s completely new. The meme-stock sharehol=
ders are thousands of individuals, sure, but thanks to social media they ar=
e far more enthusiastic and coordinated than the retail investors of the pa=
st.=C2=A0If you=E2=80=99re the chief executive officer of a meme-stock comp=
any, and you displease your retail shareholders, they probably can=E2=80=99=
t mount a proxy fight or a hostile takeover, but they=C2=A0can=C2=A0say mea=
n things about you on social media, possibly in ways that you find very per=
sonally unpleasant. Also your stock will probably be very volatile. Also ma=
ybe you=C2=A0will=C2=A0be vulnerable to a hostile takeover=C2=A0from an act=
ivist who is better able to harness meme-stock investors than you are.=09Al=
so, in 2024, retail shareholders mostly=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t vote=C2=A0at sha=
reholder meetings, so any sort of corporate governance that relies on votin=
g might not work at meme-stock companies. We have talked about things like =
AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s APE preferred stock, designed to =
get around shareholder voting requirements, because if you=E2=80=99re a mem=
e-stock company you may not be able to get enough shareholders to vote on w=
hatever you need them to vote on.

Here is a fun paper from=C2=A0Dhruv Aggarwal,=C2=A0Albert H. Choi and=C2=A0=
Yoon-Ho Alex Lee=C2=A0titled =E2=80=9CRetail Investors and Corporate Govern=
ance: Evidence from Zero-Commission Trading=E2=80=9D:
We examine the effects of the sudden abolition of trading commissions by ma=
jor online brokerages in 2019, which lowered stock market entry costs for r=
etail investors, on corporate governance. Firms already popular with retail=
