<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meme stocks are basically companies wh=
ose shares are largely held by enthusiastic retail investors who are on Red=
dit a lot.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In some ways, this rese=
mbles Phase 2 of my stylized history: You have diffuse retail shareholders =
and powerful managers who run the companies; the tools that institutional i=
nvestors developed to supervise managers in Phase 3 don=E2=80=99t really wo=
rk at companies that don=E2=80=99t have institutional investors.=C2=A0</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In other ways, though, it=E2=80=99s co=
mpletely new. The meme-stock shareholders are thousands of individuals, sur=
e, but thanks to social media they are far more enthusiastic and coordinate=
d than the retail investors of the past.=C2=A0If you=E2=80=99re the chief e=
xecutive officer of a meme-stock company, and you displease your retail sha=
reholders, they probably can=E2=80=99t mount a proxy fight or a hostile tak=
eover, but they=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>say mean things about you on social =
media, possibly in ways that you find very personally unpleasant. Also your=
 stock will probably be very volatile. Also maybe you=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</=
em>be vulnerable to a hostile takeover=C2=A0from an <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34726086.260360/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDQvbWFjeS1zLXRhcmdldGVkLWJ5LW1l=
bWUtYWN0aXZpc3RzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMTgyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWw=
mdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMxOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZX=
