<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a fun paper from=C2=A0Dhruv Aggarwal,=
=C2=A0Albert H. Choi and=C2=A0Yoon-Ho Alex Lee=C2=A0titled =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34726086.260360/aHR0cHM6L=
y9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQ3MDg0OTY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6bc62db9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Retail Investors and Corporate Gover=
nance: Evidence from Zero-Commission Trading</a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We examine the effects of the sudd=
en abolition of trading commissions by major online brokerages in 2019, whi=
ch lowered stock market entry costs for retail investors, on corporate gove=
rnance. Firms already popular with retail investors experienced positive ab=
normal returns around the abolition of commissions. Firms with positive abn=
ormal returns in response to commission-free trading subsequently saw a dec=
rease in institutional ownership, a decrease in shareholder voting, and a d=
eterioration in environmental, social, and corporate governance (ESG) metri=
cs. Finally, these firms were more likely to adopt bylaw amendments to redu=
ce the percentage of shares needed for a quorum at shareholder meetings. Ou=
r results provide new insights into the effects of entry costs on investors=
 and the role of retail investors in corporate governance.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I like here is just the method =
of identifying meme stocks: Loosely speaking, a meme stock is a company who=
se stock went up when retail brokerage commissions went away. If your stock=
 went up when retail commissions went to zero, that=C2=A0<em>suggests=C2=A0=
</em>that you are a company beloved by retail investors, and it turns out t=
hat that fact correlates with a decrease in institutional ownership.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then that fact =E2=80=94=C2=A0quasi-meme-s=
tock-ness =E2=80=94=C2=A0also correlates with other facts that you=E2=80=99=
d expect about meme stocks. For instance: Retail shareholders don=E2=80=99t=
 vote. (=E2=80=9CStudying proposal-level voting data, we find that these fi=
rms saw a significant jump in non-voting after the introduction of zero-com=
mission trading,=E2=80=9D the paper says.) Therefore, the companies needed =
to lower their shareholder vote requirements if they=E2=80=99re going to ge=
t anything done.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, it sort of looks as if ESG is=C2=A0a con=
cern of institutional investors and retail shareholders don=E2=80=99t care:=
 =E2=80=9CThis deterioration in ESG scores is consistent with an increase i=
n the (relative) influence of retail investors, who typically exert less pr=
essure on corporations to prioritize ESG than institutional players.=E2=80=
=9D But this is maybe not the whole story:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Disaggregating ESG performance int=
o the sub-scores for environmental (=E2=80=9CE=E2=80=9D), social (=E2=80=9C=
S=E2=80=9D), and corporate governance (=E2=80=9CG=E2=80=9D) issues, we find=
 that the post-2019 decline for the treatment group is concentrated in the =
governance component. We find no significant change in these companies=E2=
=80=99 performance on =E2=80=9CE=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D issues aft=
er the advent of zero-commission trading. Therefore, the best reading of th=
e decrease in treated firms=E2=80=99 ESG scores could be that the quality o=
f their corporate governance declined after 2019, rather than that retail i=
nvestor influence caused them to become less =E2=80=9Cprosocial.=E2=80=9D T=
o investigate the determinants of this decrease in =E2=80=9CG,=E2=80=9D we =
analyze changes in several corporate governance outcomes that retail invest=
ors could have affected: staggered boards, poison pills, majority voting st=
andard, board independence, and board gender diversity. We find that treate=
d firms become significantly less likely to have a majority shareholder vot=
ing standard for director elections after the introduction of zero-commissi=
on trading. We find no evidence, however, that treated firms perform any di=
fferently when we study staggered boards, poison pills, board independence,=
 or gender diversity. Given our prior finding regarding retail investors=E2=
=80=99 non-participation in voting, we believe it is significant that the o=
nly weakened corporate governance outcome we observe is directly related to=
 the process of shareholder voting.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMeme-stock companies are worse at ESG=
=E2=80=9D is not quite right; the story might be more like =E2=80=9Cmeme-st=
ock companies are worse at=C2=A0<em>shareholder voting</em>, because their =
shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote, and some shareholder voting procedures go =
into their ESG scores.=E2=80=9D</p>
